\begin_layout Section
Two-dimensional organisation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the inception of cytogenetics, it has been known that not all chromosomes
 are the same.
 The development of chromosome banding techniques in the 1970s allowed detailed
 human karyotypes to be determined, complete with differential staining
 of regions within each chromosome, termed 'bands' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Caspersson1970"

\end_inset

.
 Banding assays can show regions of heterochromatin and euchromatin, highlightin
g the variation in characteristics across regions of the genome 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Trask2002"

\end_inset

.
 The sequencing of the human genome allowed detailed analysis of GC content,
 gene density and repetitive sequence content 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lander2001"

\end_inset

.
 Versteeg 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 integrated a multitude of 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "SAGE"
description "Serial analysis of gene expression"

\end_inset

 SAGE tag expression profiles from different cell types into the genomic
 map and built on earlier work defined regions of high transcriptional activity,
 called ridges 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Versteeg2003,Caron2001"

\end_inset

.
 They found ridges to be gene-dense, highly transcribed, have a high GC
 content and low LINE repeat density.
 These features are based purely on the underlying sequence content and
 so do not vary amongst cell types.
 The different ridges and anti-ridges were found to contain different classes
 of genes, with weakly expressed genes clustering within anti-ridges and
 clusters of highly expressed housekeeping genes found predominantly in
 ridges 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Versteeg2003"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whilst the two-dimensional organisation of the genome cannot completely
 explain the degree of complexity found with transcriptional control, these
 studies demonstrate that the order of sequence within the genome is not
 random, and has a large effect on the way that DNA content is interpreted.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Chromosome Territories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interphase nucleus is a highly structured organelle.
 As chromosomes decondense after metaphase they retain some degree of structure,
 forming 'chromosome territories' (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CT"
description "Chromosome territory"

\end_inset

CTs) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cremer2001"

\end_inset

.
 Circumstantial evidence for interphase organisation of chromosomes has
 existed for a long time, first suggested by Carl Rabl in 1885 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rabl1885"

\end_inset

.
 Oberservations by Stack 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 using microscopy with giemsa-band staining suggested that chromosomes retained
 some degree of organisation during interphase 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stack1977"

\end_inset

, and in 1982 Cremer 
\emph on
et al., 
\emph default
showed that interphase chromosomes exist in 'territories' by studying the
 pattern of DNA damage in metaphase chromosomes after spot irradiation in
 during interphase 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cremer1982"

\end_inset

.
 The subsequent development of 'chromosome paints', a method to visualise
 entire- or part- chromosomes with fluorescence 
\emph on
in-situ
\emph default
 hybridisation (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "FISH"
description "Fluorescence in-situ hybridisation"

\end_inset

FISH), confirmed these findings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schardin1985a,Manuelidis1985,Bolzer2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

