\begin_layout Subsection
CTs and transcription
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's known that for some but not all genes, positioning at the nuclear periphery
 correlates with reduced gene expression 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kosak2002,Dietzel2004,Zink2004a"

\end_inset

.
 To investigate whether transcriptional activity is the cause or effect
 of this positioning effect, two groups published studies which artificially
 tethered genomic regions to the inner nuclear membrane using
\emph on
 
\emph default
Lac operators 
\emph on
(lacO)
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Finlan2008,Reddy2008"

\end_inset

.
 Both groups observed a decrease in the transcriptional activity of the
 regions when tethered, an effect that was ablated when cells were treated
 with trichostatin A (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "TSA"
description "Trichostatin A"

\end_inset

TSA) to inhibit class I and class II histone deacetylases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Finlan2008"

\end_inset

, though this effect does not appear to apply to all loci 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kumaran2008"

\end_inset

.
 Whilst these studies suggest that it is nuclear positioning that leads
 to transcriptional effects, a study by Croft 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 showed that inhibition of transcription causes a reversible change in CT
 position 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Croft1999"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Large scale rearrangements of CTs have also been observed during cell differenti
ation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stadler2004,Szczerbal2009"

\end_inset

, likely due to changes in transcriptional profiles and chromatin remodelling.
 As such, it seems that there is a dynamic interplay between CT positioning
 and transcription - gross transcriptional patterns may drive the position
 of chromosomes within the nucleus, and those positions may in turn affect
 the transcription of the genes they contain.
 Interestingly, derivative chromosomes that result from balanced translocations
 affect the organisation of CTs within the nucleus 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Harewood2010"

\end_inset

, raising the possibility that the global changes in gene expression observed
 after oncogenic translocations could be in part due to changes in genome
 organisation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Harewood2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chromosome territory dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The movement of chromatin loci within the nucleus is known to be largely
 due to local brownian motion, or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constrained diffusion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and seems to be limited by attachment to a nuclear cytoskeleton, nucleoli
 and the inner nuclear membrane 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Marshall1997,Chubb2002"

\end_inset

.
 Other studies have shown a mixture of local diffusion and larger, active
 movements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vazquez2001"

\end_inset

.
 Chuang 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 studied Chinese hamster ovary (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "CHO"
description "Chinese hamster ovary cells"

\end_inset

CHO) cells after stimulation with a transcriptional activator and analysed
 the movement of the target chromosome from the nuclear periphery to the
 interior of the nucleus 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chuang2006"

\end_inset

.
 They found that chromosome movements happened in rapid unidirectional bursts,
 suggesting an active mechanism.
 This was supported by a later study in human fibroblast cells by Mehta
 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 who demonstrated chromosome movement only 15 minutes after serum starvation,
 a process that was ablated by the inhibition of actin and myosin polymerisation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mehta2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chromatin decondensation and the inter-chromosomal space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the study of whole chromosome positioning, there has been
 a great deal of research into the positioning of individual sequences relative
 to their chromosome territory.
 Early studies suggested that transcribed genes were found at the surface
 of chromosome territories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zirbel1993"

\end_inset

 leading to a model whereby transcriptionally inactive genes are buried
 within territories and expressed genes contact in an inter-chromosome domain
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "ICD"
description "Inter-chromosome domain"

\end_inset

ICD) where they can contact the transcriptional machinery 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cremer1993"

\end_inset

.
 This model gained support due to studies showing genes at the periphery
 of CTs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kurz1996"

\end_inset

 and new techniques to visualise the ICD using microscopy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bridger1998"

\end_inset

.
 A number of FISH studies showed genes moving away from their territories
 in large loops upon activation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Volpi2000,Mahy2002a,Chambeyron2004"

\end_inset

, suggesting that they may be recruited to the ICD for transcription.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite these case studies, looping is not a prerequisite for transcription;
 other DNA-FISH studies have shown transcription within the volume of chromosome
 territories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Verschure1999,Mahy2002"

\end_inset

.
 Osborne 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 showed that actively transcribed 
\emph on
Uros
\emph default
 gene is more frequently outside it's CT than the inactive gene 
\emph on
Fgfr2
\emph default
, though this position was not necessary for transcription, suggesting that
 actively transcribed genes may preferentially locate to the surface of
 CTs, but this alone is not sufficient to drive transcription 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Osborne2004"

\end_inset

.
 As such, it has been suggested that the inter-chromosomal domain model
 should be renamed the inter-
\emph on
chromatin
\emph default
 domain model, whereby chromosomes are invaginated with channels and subdivided
 into ~1 Mbp domains of chromatin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cremer2001"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chromosome territory intermingling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A question that followed immediately on from the discovery of loops extending
 from chromosome territories was that of chromosome intermingling.
 Mathematical modelling approaches suggested that irradiation induced DNA
 damage corresponded to the intermingling of chromosome territories 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Holley2002,Hlatky2002"

\end_inset

.
 This was later backed up with a study by Branco and Pombo, who studied
 thin cryosections of nuclei with high resolution light and electron microscopy;
 they found that there is significant intermingling of chromatin between
 chromosome territories, and that the extent of this intermingling correlated
 strongly with previously recorded irradiation induced translocation frequencies
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Branco2006"

\end_inset

.
 In support of chromosome intermingling, the 
\emph on
HoxB
\emph default
 extra-chromosomal loops found to extend from the chromosome territory upon
 gene activation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chambeyron2004"

\end_inset

 were found to make increased 
\emph on
trans
\emph default
 chromosomal interactions whilst looping out 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wurtele2006"

\end_inset

, suggesting that the loops contact other chromosomes rather than occupying
 an empty inter-chromosomal space.
\end_layout

