\begin_layout Subsection
Specialised transcription factories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the demonstration that genes shared transcription factories, a number
 of groups postulated that specific genes may colocalise at a subset of
 transcription factories.
 The self-organising principle applied to transcription factories would
 predict this; just as the local concentration of active RNA Polymerase
 II is elevated by the clustering of transcribed units, the local concentration
 of transcription factors that bind to those transcribed units will also
 be elevated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cook2002"

\end_inset

.
 Genes that diffuse to a transcription factory already engaged with other
 genes that share the same factors are more likely to engage and be transcribed
 themselves 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bartlett2006"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, genes regulated by common transcription factors appear to cluster
 within specific chromosomes in yeast 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Janga2008"

\end_inset

 and testis-specific genes are found clustered in 
\emph on
Drosophila
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Boutanaev2002"

\end_inset

 - genes clustered in linear sequence are more likely to associate in three
 dimensions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
